Hi,

In the code below, in Save function while storing the value of NDArray, default value of header is set to `kMXAPINDArrayListMagic = 0x112`; Whereas in LOAD function if header value is set to be kMXAPINDArrayListMagic, it will provide `CHECK(header == kMXAPINDArrayListMagic)
      << "Invalid NDArray file format";` related issue. Do I need to pass on some custom value as head to successfully load the NDArray value.

`const uint64_t kMXAPINDArrayListMagic = 0x112;

void NDArray::Save(dmlc::Stream\* fo,
                   const std::vector<NDArray>& data,
                   const std::vectorstd::string& names) {
  uint64_t header = kMXAPINDArrayListMagic, reserved = 0;
  fo->Write(&header, sizeof(header));
  fo->Write(&reserved, sizeof(reserved));
  fo->Write(data);
  fo->Write(names);
}

void NDArray::Load(dmlc::Stream\* fi,
                   std::vector<NDArray>\* data,
                   std::vectorstd::string\* keys) {
  uint64_t header, reserved;
  CHECK(fi->Read(&header))
      << "Invalid NDArray file format";
  CHECK(fi->Read(&reserved))
      << "Invalid NDArray file format";
  CHECK(header == kMXAPINDArrayListMagic)
      << "Invalid NDArray file format";
  CHECK(fi->Read(data))`

## Description
Temporary workspace in operator can only be allocated once. This becomes a problem if you have some computed values based on which you need to allocate more memory. For my particular case, I am trying to compute the number of non zero columns for a csr matrix so that I can only allocate the required memory before launching the kernel. There are two steps here. First step requires me to allocate a temp workspace to store true values corresponding to non zero columns. The second step requires me to use this total number of non zero columns to allocate the second temp space.

MXNet commit hash:
399ac038da885ff3dce8e43bcbdf76bb62522e73

## Steps to reproduce

In src/resource.cc, if the new size is greater than currently allocated temp workspace size it frees the current temp workspace and allocates the new one. Otherwise it reuses the first one. This means that there is no way to create two temp workspaces where the second one is bigger than the first. 

Is there any specific reason for this behavior? Is there any plan to fix it?
```
inline void* GetSpace(size_t size) {
  if (handle.size >= size) return handle.dptr;
  if (handle.size != 0) {
     Storage::Get()->DirectFree(handle);
  }
  handle = Storage::Get()->Alloc(size, ctx);
  return handle.dptr;
}
```

Currently, if a Task A (such as PrepareResources) depends on products of Task B (such as IvyResolve) and Task B depends on the products of Task A, the execution will depend on whichever Goal/Task gets visited first.
This is an error case - An exception should be thrown if a cyclic dependency like this is detected.

For example,

    class PrepareResources():
      def prepare():
        round_manager.require('ivy_jar_products')
      def product_type():
        return 'resources_by_target'

    class IvyResolve():
      def prepare():
        round_manager.require('resources_by_target')
      def product_type()
        return 'ivy_jar_products'

These declarations should throw a cyclic dependency exception.

